    • Constructor Detail

      • PPMecanumControllerCommand

        public PPMecanumControllerCommand​(PathPlannerTrajectory trajectory,
                                  Supplier<Pose2d> poseSupplier,
                                  PIDController xController,
                                  PIDController yController,
                                  PIDController rotationController,
                                  Consumer<ChassisSpeeds> outputChassisSpeeds,
                                  boolean useAllianceColor,
                                  Subsystem... requirements)
        Constructs a new PPMecanumControllerCommand that when executed will follow the provided trajectory. The user should implement a velocity PID on the desired output wheel velocities.

        Note: The controllers will *not* set the output to zero upon completion of the path - this is left to the user, since it is not appropriate for paths with non-stationary end-states.

        Parameters:
        trajectory - The Pathplanner trajectory to follow.
        poseSupplier - A function that supplies the robot pose - use one of the odometry classes to provide this.
        xController - The Trajectory Tracker PID controller for the robot's x position.
        yController - The Trajectory Tracker PID controller for the robot's y position.
        rotationController - The Trajectory Tracker PID controller for angle for the robot.
        outputChassisSpeeds - A consumer for a ChassisSpeeds object containing the output speeds.
        useAllianceColor - Should the path states be automatically transformed based on alliance color? In order for this to work properly, you MUST create your path on the blue side of the field.
        requirements - The subsystems to require.

        Constructs a new PPMecanumControllerCommand that when executed will follow the provided trajectory. The user should implement a velocity PID on the desired output wheel velocities.

        Note: The controllers will *not* set the output to zero upon completion of the path - this is left to the user, since it is not appropriate for paths with non-stationary end-states.

        Parameters:
        trajectory - The Pathplanner trajectory to follow.
        poseSupplier - A function that supplies the robot pose - use one of the odometry classes to provide this.
        kinematics - The kinematics for the robot drivetrain.
        xController - The Trajectory Tracker PID controller for the robot's x position.
        yController - The Trajectory Tracker PID controller for the robot's y position.
        rotationController - The Trajectory Tracker PID controller for angle for the robot.
        maxWheelVelocityMetersPerSecond - The maximum velocity of a drivetrain wheel.
        outputWheelSpeeds - A MecanumDriveWheelSpeeds object containing the output wheel speeds.
        useAllianceColor - Should the path states be automatically transformed based on alliance color? In order for this to work properly, you MUST create your path on the blue side of the field.
        requirements - The subsystems to require.

        public static void setLoggingCallbacks​(Consumer<PathPlannerTrajectory> logActiveTrajectory,
                                       Consumer<Pose2d> logTargetPose,
                                       Consumer<ChassisSpeeds> logSetpoint,
                                       BiConsumer<Translation2d,​Rotation2d> logError)
        Set custom logging callbacks for this command to use instead of the default configuration of pushing values to SmartDashboard
        Parameters:
        logActiveTrajectory - Consumer that accepts a PathPlannerTrajectory representing the active path. This will be called whenever a PPMecanumControllerCommand starts
        logTargetPose - Consumer that accepts a Pose2d representing the target pose while path following
        logSetpoint - Consumer that accepts a ChassisSpeeds object representing the setpoint speeds
        logError - BiConsumer that accepts a Translation2d and Rotation2d representing the error while path following
